+---
+name: botfix
+description: "Use when the user wants to debug or fix a trading bot bug, especially around fills, reconciliation, degraded modes, fees, ledger state, governor behavior, or dashboard mismatches. Examples: /botfix, 'why is cycle profit wrong?', 'trace this fill bug'."
+---
+
+# Botfix
+
+Use this skill for trading bot debugging and bug-fix work that needs disciplined analysis before code changes.
+
+## Required Inputs
+
+Ask the user for:
+
+- Observed behavior
+- Expected behavior
+- Relevant log lines, timestamps, or screenshots of logs
+
+## Workflow
+
+1. Run `git pull` to sync with remote before starting analysis.
+2. Collect the user's observed behavior, expected behavior, and log evidence.
+3. Enter the analysis phase. Do not change code yet.
+
+## Analysis Phase
+
+Identify all code paths that could produce the reported behavior.
+
+For each candidate path, report:
+
+- `file:line`
+- Trigger condition
+- Data flow into and out of the path
+
+Mandatory checklist:
+
+- [ ] Normal fill flow (`state_machine.transition` -> `FillEvent`)
+- [ ] Startup reconciliation (`main.py` init -> ledger replay)
+- [ ] Orphan recovery (`RecoveryFillEvent` and `CancelEvent`)
+- [ ] Degraded modes (`S0_long_only`, `S0_short_only`, `S1a_short_only`, `S1b_long_only`)
+- [ ] Governor post-tick (growth snapshots, recovery TTL)
+- [ ] Fee path (`config.MAKER_FEE_PCT` -> cycle profit -> ledger -> dashboard)
+
+Present the analysis clearly, then stop and wait for explicit user confirmation before writing code.
+
+## Test Phase
+
+After user confirmation:
+
+1. Write a failing test that reproduces the bug.
+2. Run `pytest` and confirm the new test fails for the expected reason.
+
+## Fix Phase
+
+1. Implement the minimal fix that covers every identified path, not just the easiest one.
+2. Run the new test and the relevant broader test suite.
+3. Iterate until the new test and the suite are green.
+4. Summarize the root cause, the fix, and any paths that were validated.
+
+## Finish
+
+Ask whether the user wants to run `/push`.
